<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" ng-app="git-app">

<% include ../partials/header.ejs %>

    <!-- <body ng-controller="main_view_controller"> -->

    <body>
        <h1>Github interface using API (eventually!)</h1>
        <h2>{{person.name}}</h2>
        <!-- navbars top right -->
        <!-- on click buttons should go to a btn-default bootstrap -->
        <div class="level_1 nav-buttons">
            <div class="level_2">
                <div class="level_3">
                    <a href="#!settings">
                        <button ng-route="" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">Settings
                        </button>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div class="level_3">
                    <!-- <a href="gists.ejs "> -->
                    <button class="btn btn-info btn-lg" title="https://gist.github.com/ ">Gists</button>
                    <!-- </a> -->
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="level_2">
                <div class="level_3">
                    <!-- <a href="help.ejs "> -->
                    <button class="btn btn-info btn-lg" title="https://help.github.com/ ">Help</button>
                    <!-- </a> -->
                </div>
                <div class="level_3">
                    <!-- <a href="signout.html"> -->
                    <button class="tn btn-primary btn-lg" title="&lt;button type=&quot; submit &quot; class=&quot;dropdown-item
        dropdown-signout &quot; data-ga-click=&quot; Header, sign out, icon:logout &quot;&gt; Sign out &lt;/button&gt;">Sign out</button>
                    <!-- </a> -->
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- main 4 views -->
        <div class="container">
            <h3>gm.dragDrop</h3>
            <h3>Reordering</h3>
            <!--<p>Demonstrates using
                <code>gm-on-hover</code> to apply logic and reorder items. Also demonstrates drag area using
                <code>gm-drag-handle</code>
            </p> -->
            <!-- ng-class="box-{{$index}} " use this to have unique classes for the iterations of the repeat. Thinking of responsive and saving those to database as user preferences???-->
            <!-- look at https://www.w3schools.com/angular/angular_routing.asp -->
            <div class="list-group">
                <div class="view_level_3" ng-repeat="item in orderedItems | orderBy: 'order'" gm-draggable="item" gm-on-invalid-drop="reset"
                    gm-on-drop="reorder" gm-on-hover="onHover(item)">
                    {{item.value}}
                    <div class="pull-right gm-drag-handle">
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-move"></span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="view_level_1">
            <div class="view_level_2">
                <div id="view1 " class="view_level_3" ng-view>
                    <h3 class="title">Repositories</h3>
                    <div class="inside "></div>
                </div>
                <div id="view2 " class="view_level_3" ng-view>Contributions
                    <div class="inside "></div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="view_level_2">
                <div id="view3 " class="view_level_3" ng-view>Followers
                    <div class="inside "></div>
                </div>
                <div id="view4 " class="view_level_3" ng-view>Following
                    <div class="inside"></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <p>Additional functionality (likely as an additional features)
            <br>Likely if can use some angular directives like:
            <br>ngmodel
            <br>ngclick (obviously) also function on a click
            <br>ngrepeat in someway (mostlikely a list/table), could be selecting (or creating) tags and showing popularity from
            api as a type of top 10 with number of repos using x technology (e.g. react, angular/whatever???
        </p>
    </body>

</html>